I'll stick to verifiable facts from news coverage (e.g., from Fox News, Daily Mail, and conservative outlets like The Blaze) and social media trends.  Who Started the Outrage? The initial wave of controversy was sparked by conservative influencers and social media users who framed the logo change as part of a broader "woke" corporate agenda to erase traditional American imagery. Specifically:  Jack Posobiec, a prominent right-wing commentator and former One America News host, was one of the earliest and most influential voices. On February 28, 2023, he posted on X (formerly Twitter) about the logo update, claiming it was Cracker Barrel "going woke" by modernizing their rustic, Southern-themed branding. His post quickly went viral, amassing thousands of retweets and likes, and set the tone for the backlash. Posobiec has a history of amplifying culture-war issues to conservative audiences.    This was amplified by other online personalities like Benny Johnson (a conservative podcaster and Turning Point USA contributor) and various MAGA-aligned accounts on X and Facebook. They shared side-by-side comparisons of the old vs. new logo, accusing the chain of pandering to progressive values at the expense of its "heritage" (e.g., claims that the update diluted the "country" aesthetic tied to Southern traditions). The outrage started organically on social media but was fueled by these influencers' posts, which predated major news coverage.  The controversy didn't come from Cracker Barrel's customers initially—many regular patrons were unaware of the change until it was highlighted online. Cracker Barrel has clarified that the update was a minor design tweak for clarity and modernity, not a political statement, but that didn't stop the narrative from spreading.  Who Fired Up MAGA Over It? MAGA supporters were particularly riled up because the story fit into a larger narrative of cultural erosion under "woke capitalism" (similar to boycotts of Bud Light or Target). The key figure who supercharged the MAGA angle was Donald Trump Jr. (Don Jr.), son of former President Donald Trump and a vocal MAGA proponent:  On March 1, 2023, Don Jr. posted on X about the logo change, calling it an example of corporations "destroying their brands to appease the woke mob." His tweet received over 100,000 engagements and directly tied it to MAGA talking points about preserving "real America" against liberal influences. This post acted as rocket fuel, drawing in high-profile MAGA figures like Candace Owens (who echoed the sentiment on her show) and Matt Walsh (from The Daily Wire), who used it to criticize corporate virtue-signaling.  Broader MAGA amplification came from outlets like Fox News (which ran segments on the "boycott") and conservative radio hosts such as Sean Hannity, who mentioned it on his show as part of a pattern of anti-traditional changes by brands. This led to organized calls for boycotts within MAGA communities on platforms like Truth Social and Telegram, with hashtags like #BoycottCrackerBarrel trending briefly.  Context and Aftermath The outrage peaked in early March 2023, with Cracker Barrel's stock dipping slightly amid boycott threats, but it fizzled out quickly as the change was revealed to be non-controversial (just a cleaner font and color adjustment). No evidence suggests involvement from left-leaning groups or official political campaigns; it was almost entirely a right-wing, grassroots (influencer-driven) reaction. If you're looking for primary sources, check Posobiec's and Don Jr.'s X archives from late February/early March 2023, or coverage from outlets like Newsweek or The Hill.
